			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Exended Notes(Benefical  spells only nerf)<a name="67040"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Oct 15 04 11:07 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I think that using an instrument to play a song with a range ought to increase its range by some percent of the instrument modifier.  If not for our targeted songs like mezz or lull, then at least for the AE and group songs.
<br />

<br />
Other classes need only one focus item to increase range on all of their spells (not sure if theres a seperate focus for detrimental range and beneficial range, but at the max they need 2 items) and then they wear the item(s) and that's it.  If a bard wanted to increase range on their War Song of the Vah Shir, they'd have to equip brass, or if they wanted to increase the range on Chorus of Marr, they'd equip lute.  Singing-only songs should have range increased by Amp.
<br />

<br />
It all makes perfect roleplaying sense.  The mere term &quot;Amplification&quot; suggests increasing the intensity of something.  More powerful sound waves would travel further, in addition to having a more potent effect on all ears within that range.  The same would apply to those more powerful instruments.  It seems to me that a &quot;Thunderous Drum of Karana&quot; could be heard from further away than a &quot;Hand Drum.&quot;
<br />

<br />
Besides, this would give bards incentive to use instruments in combat, would make the epic a must-have item again to some who may use better ratio weapons, etc.
<br />

<br />
Btw, I am new here, so this whole thing may have been proposed before.  I have no idea.  Anyhow, just thinking.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
